courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. To understand definition, scope, basic principles and problems in biomedical engineering;
2. Able to apply technology to medicine and biology;
3. To understand contemporary issues and roles of engineering applied to biological systems; and
4. To understand the importance of professional ethics.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. Able to describe the functions of the major organ systems of the body, including the endocrine, nervous, cardiovascular, kidney and respiratory systems;
2. Able to explain the basic anatomy of the human body especially with respect to the skull, vertebral columns and limbs;
3. Able to describe the basic chemical constituents of the body and their functions, and the concepts of genomics, bioinformatics & protein engineering;
4. Able to explain the concepts of tissue engineering, biomechanics and rehabilitation engineering;
5. Able to explain the origins of neuronal and other bioelectric signals and their recording methods; and
6. Able to elucidate case studies that illustrate the importance of medical sciences in relation to biomedical engineering.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. Understand fundamentals of medical robotics;
2. Know how to derive the forward kinematics of robot manipulator;
3. Be familiar with the inverse kinematics of robot manipulator;
4. Understand human-robots interface and its importance in medical robots;
5. Understand tele-robotics and its medical applications;
6. Understand fundamentals of robot control;
7. Be knowledgeable with novel robotic applications in medical care; and
8. Be knowledgeable with surgical robotics.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. Able to recognize the importance of bioinformatics;
2. Able to perform basic protein and DNA sequence analyses, including alignment of sequence;
3. Able to do basic searches in common databases to aid in applied bioinformatics analyses;
4. Able to perform basic statistical analysis; and
5. Able to describe the fundamental aspects of phylogenetic trees, scoring matrices, pattern recognition, clustering and structural prediction.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. To understand the principles and clinical applications of image guided and non-image guide computer aided surgeries;
2. To understand the principles and clinical application of robot assisted surgery;
3. To understand the principles and application of e-medicine with clinical management system;
4. To understand the principles of Virtual Reality and surgical simulation and Augmented reality and image-guided minimally invasive surgery;
5. To introduce the use of telerobotics in surgery; and
6. With a variety of proposed projects, students will have a first hand information and practical experience on the further understanding of the above knowledge conveyed in the lectures.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. To use the basic digital image processing background to understand image acquisition, sampling and reconstruction, image segmentation, image filtering;
2. To use fundamental concept for medical visualization;
3. To understand the basic physical principles for clinical applications of several relevant clinical medical imaging devices, including X-ray fluoroscopy, radiography, ultrasound, computed tomography (CT) and imaging guided therapy;
4. To be able to follow the terahertz principle to apply terahertz imaging and spectroscopy in biomedicine;
5. To understand the basics of cellular and molecular imaging and major imaging modalities, including Laser Scanning Confocal Microscopy, Light and Fluorescence Microscopy and In vivo molecular imaging for small animal;
6. To understand the basis of Medical Imaging Based Bone Densitometry, including DXA, pQCT, and microCT) and their application in diagnosis of osteoporosis; and
7. To understand the basic principles of medical imaging-based Finite Element Analysis (FEA).

Upon completion, students should have achieved the following outcomes:

1. Understand **ageing mechanisms** at molecular, cellular, and systemic levels;

2. Explore **global business dynamics** beyond the early-stage biotech and longevity industry;

3. Navigate complex **regulatory** environments for Bio/Pharma and Longevity-related Products and services; and

4. Apply **bioinformatics** tools in both translational studies and clinical omics to develop healthcare solutions.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to:
1. apply knowledge of engineering and science to medical applications;
2. obtain hands-on practical experience;
3. identify, formulate, and solve biomedical engineering problems; and
4. write a technical report and effectively give an oral presentation.

